<Link id="l00026" /><CodeLine lineNumber="26"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Provides amortized O(1) random access to a CodeView type stream.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00027" /><CodeLine lineNumber="27"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Normally to access a type from a type stream, you must know its byte</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00028" /><CodeLine lineNumber="28"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// offset into the type stream, because type records are variable-lengthed.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00029" /><CodeLine lineNumber="29"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// However, this is not the way we prefer to access them.  For example, given</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00030" /><CodeLine lineNumber="30"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// a symbol record one of the fields may be the TypeIndex of the symbol&#39;s</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="31"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// type record.  Or given a type record such as an array type, there might</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="32"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// be a TypeIndex for the element type.  Sequential access is perfect when</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="33"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// we&#39;re just dumping every entry, but it&#39;s very poor for real world usage.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Type streams in PDBs contain an additional field which is a list of pairs</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="36"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// containing indices and their corresponding offsets, roughly every ~8KB of</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="37"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// record data.  This general idea need not be confined to PDBs though.  By</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="38"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// supplying such an array, the producer of a type stream can allow the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="39"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// consumer much better access time, because the consumer can find the nearest</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00040" /><CodeLine lineNumber="40"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// index in this array, and do a linear scan forward only from there.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="41"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="42"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// LazyRandomTypeCollection implements this algorithm, but additionally goes</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00043" /><CodeLine lineNumber="43"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// one step further by caching offsets of every record that has been visited at</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00044" /><CodeLine lineNumber="44"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// least once.  This way, even repeated visits of the same record will never</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00045" /><CodeLine lineNumber="45"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// require more than one linear scan.  For a type stream of N elements divided</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00046" /><CodeLine lineNumber="46"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// into M chunks of roughly equal size, this yields a worst case lookup time</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00047" /><CodeLine lineNumber="47"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// of O(N/M) and an amortized time of O(1).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00048" /><CodeLine lineNumber="48" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/codeview/lazyrandomtypecollection"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/codeview/lazyrandomtypecollection/#afad57506ce439940f94785edf80084da">LazyRandomTypeCollection</a> : </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">public</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/codeview/typecollection">TypeCollection</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>
